To build a traffic light in Vue, the core idea is to manage the current light's state using a reactive variable and cycle through the states at set intervals using `setInterval`.

### Step 1 — Define Traffic Light States
First, define the possible states of the traffic light (red, green, yellow) and their associated durations. This makes the logic clear and easily configurable.
```vue
<script setup>
import { ref, onMounted, onUnmounted } from 'vue';

const lightStates = [
  { name: 'red', duration: 3000, color: 'red' },
  { name: 'green', duration: 4000, color: 'green' },
  { name: 'yellow', duration: 1000, color: 'yellow' }
];
const currentLightIndex = ref(0);
let intervalId = null;
</script>
```

### Step 2 — Implement State Cycling Logic
Create a function to advance the light to the next state, resetting to the beginning when the end is reached. Use `setInterval` to call this function based on the current light's duration.
```vue
<script setup>
// ... (previous code)

const advanceLight = () => {
  currentLightIndex.value = (currentLightIndex.value + 1) % lightStates.length;
  startTimer();
};

const startTimer = () => {
  if (intervalId) {
    clearInterval(intervalId);
  }
  const currentLight = lightStates[currentLightIndex.value];
  intervalId = setInterval(advanceLight, currentLight.duration);
};

onMounted(startTimer);
onUnmounted(() => {
  if (intervalId) {
    clearInterval(intervalId);
  }
});
</script>
```

### Step 3 — Render the Traffic Light UI
Display three circles, each representing a light. Conditionally apply a CSS class or style to highlight the `currentLight` based on its `name` or `index`.
```vue
<template>
  <div class="traffic-light">
    <div
      v-for="(light, index) in lightStates"
      :key="light.name"
      class="light-bulb"
      :class="{ active: index === currentLightIndex }"
      :style="{ backgroundColor: index === currentLightIndex ? light.color : 'gray' }"
    ></div>
  </div>
</template>

<style scoped>
.traffic-light {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  gap: 10px;
  padding: 20px;
  border: 2px solid #333;
  border-radius: 10px;
  background-color: #222;
  width: fit-content;
}

.light-bulb {
  width: 50px;
  height: 50px;
  border-radius: 50%;
  background-color: gray; /* Default off color */
  border: 2px solid #555;
}

.light-bulb.active {
  box-shadow: 0 0 15px currentColor; /* Glow effect */
}
</style>
```

### Step 4 — Integrate into App.vue
Import and render your `TrafficLight` component in `App.vue` to see it in action.
```vue
<template>
  <h1>Traffic Light Demo</h1>
  <TrafficLight />
</template>

<script setup>
import TrafficLight from './components/TrafficLight.vue';
</script>

<style>
body {
  font-family: sans-serif;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
  margin: 0;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}
</n```

Edge Cases:

*   **Component Unmount:** Ensure `clearInterval` is called in `onUnmounted` to prevent memory leaks and unexpected behavior if the component is removed from the DOM.
*   **Initial State:** The light should start immediately upon mounting, which is handled by calling `startTimer` in `onMounted`.

